ame":"Whitbread","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English:","metonymic occupational name from Middle English <i>whit bred</i> ‘white bread’ or <i>whete bred</i> ‘wheat bread’, denoting someone who baked or sold bread of the best quality, made from wheat.","nickname for someone with a white beard, Middle English <i>whīt berd</i>."],"variants":[]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament: ‘God is gracious’.  See  <b>John</b> ."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Christopher","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From the Greek name <i>Khristophoros</i>, from <i>Khristos</i> ‘Christ’ + <i>pherein</i> ‘to bear’. This was popular among early Christians, conscious of the fact that they were metaphorically bearing Christ in their hearts. A later, over-literal interpretation of the name gave rise to the legend of a saint who actually bore the Christ-child over a stream; he is regarded as the patron of travellers. In England the name was uncommon in the Middle Ages, but became very popular in the 16th century, especially in parts of the North."],"variants":[{"name":"Kristopher","meanings":["Mainly U.S.: respelling of   Christopher ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Lord John Christopher Whitbread was born in 1345, in White Notley, Essex, England, United Kingdom, his father, John Wright I, was 78 and his mother, Dorothy Whitbread, was 72. He married Dorothy Jean Bauer in 1374, in White Notley, Essex, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 3 sons. He died in 1399, in his hometown, at the age of 54."},"et":{"1345–1399":"1345–1399","1300–Male":"1300–Surnud","1354–Female":"1354–Surnud","1375–1400":"1375–1400","1396–1429":"1396–1429","1396–1452":"1396–1452","1267–1307":"1267–1307","1273–1307":"1273–1307","1374":"13